{"id":"2212.02525","submitter":"Patrick Hager","authors":"Martin Beneke, Patrick Hager, Dominik Schwienbacher","title":"Soft-collinear gravity with fermionic matter","comments":"v2: 27 pages, matches published version","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1007/JHEP03(2023)076","report-no":"TUM-HEP-1434/22, MITP-22-097","categories":"hep-ph hep-th","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We extend the effective field theory for soft and collinear gravitons to\ninteractions with fermionic matter fields. The full theory features a local\nLorentz symmetry in addition to the usual diffeomorphisms, which requires\nincorporating the former into the soft-collinear gravity framework. The local\nLorentz symmetry gives rise to Wilson lines in the effective theory that\nstrongly resemble those in SCET for non-abelian gauge interactions, whereas the\ndiffeomorphisms can be treated in the same fashion as in the case of scalar\nmatter. The basic structure of soft-collinear gravity, which features a\nhomogeneous soft background field, giving rise to a covariant derivative and\nmultipole-expanded covariant Riemann-tensor interactions, remains unaltered and\ngeneralises in a natural way to fermion fields.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 5 Dec 2022 19:00:04 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 13 Mar 2023 21:38:58 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-04-05"}
{"id":"2212.02526","submitter":"Oliver Zier","authors":"Oliver Zier and Volker Springel","title":"Gravoturbulence in local disk simulations with an adaptive moving mesh","comments":"20 pages, 16 figures, submitted to MNRAS","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1093/mnras/stad319","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.EP astro-ph.GA astro-ph.IM astro-ph.SR","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Self-gravity plays an important role in the evolution of rotationally\nsupported systems such as protoplanetary disks, accretion disks around black\nholes, or galactic disks, as it can both feed turbulence or lead to\ngravitational fragmentation. While such systems can be studied in the shearing\nbox approximation with high local resolution, the large density contrasts that\nare possible in the case of fragmentation still limit the utility of Eulerian\ncodes with constant spatial resolution. In this paper, we present a novel\nself-gravity solver for the shearing box based on the TreePM method of the\nmoving-mesh code AREPO. The spatial gravitational resolution is adaptive which\nis important to make full use of the quasi-Lagrangian hydrodynamical resolution\nof the code. We apply our new implementation to two- and three-dimensional,\nself-gravitating disks combined with a simple $\\beta$-cooling prescription. For\nweak cooling we find a steady, gravoturbulent state, while for strong cooling\nthe formation of fragments is inevitable. To reach convergence for the critical\ncooling efficiency above which fragmentation occurs, we require a smoothing of\nthe gravitational force in the two dimensional case that mimics the\nstratification of the three-dimensional simulations. The critical cooling\nefficiency we find, $\\beta \\approx 3$, as well as box-averaged quantities\ncharacterizing the gravoturbulent state, agree well with various previous\nresults in the literature. Interestingly, we observe stochastic fragmentation\nfor $\\beta > 3$, which slightly decreases the cooling efficiency required to\nobserve fragmentation over the lifetime of a protoplanetary disk. The numerical\nmethod outlined here appears well suited to study the problem of galactic disks\nas well as magnetized, self-gravitating disks.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 5 Dec 2022 19:00:04 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-02-08"}
